Nov 20 2009 	nice little getaway	We booked this hotel because we were traveling with friends and this is where they were all staying. From the moment we drove up to the valet to the time we drove away the staff throughout the hotel and casino were friendly. Our room was on the 9th floor overlooking the pool and garden area. It was a deluxe room and was recently re-done. It was clean and the bed was comfortable. The pillows were a little flat for my liking but I was still able to sleep well. All the usual amenities were there such as soap, shampoo, conditioner, body lotion and hair dryer (not one of the usual crappy white hotel ones either) There are no refrigerators in the rooms but they are available for $15/day if you request it. There is a stocked mini-bar but I found out the hard way that if you so much as take an item out to look at it you'll be charged even if you put it right back. The front desk was nice enough about taking it off the bill. There are a few restaurants inside the Mirage. The only ones we ate at were the Carnegie Deli for breakfast (good food but slow service) and Onda (good Italian food, pricey compared to where I come from but average for Vegas, service was good) Some of our friends ate at California Pizza Kitchen and BB King and I didn't hear any complaints. It was a little chilly this time of year so we weren't able to enjoy the pool although it did look nice. We didn't go into the Secret Garden or Dolphin Habitat but that's where the white tigers are. There is internet in each room and I don't remember the rate but I thought it too much just to check our e-mail but at least it's there if you need it. There is a little business service center back near the meeting rooms where you can print your flight bording passes for free. There's also a computer room where you can go on-line and print from that charges you. But if it's just bording passes you need you can do it free. The Mirage has free parking and free valet. We found the valet very convienient. It's a decent walk from the parking garage just to get back into the lobby of the hotel. We just tipped the valet $2 each time. We didn't drive much so it was worth the money. There are liquor stores, drug stores and fast food joints on pretty much every corner. If you forgot something I would check at the Walgreens right across the street before buying it in the hotel's store. You are able to walk in public with open containers. The Mirage is pretty centrally located and is only a &quot;short&quot; walk to many of the other popular resorts. I say &quot;short&quot; because the resorts are pretty vast in size so the next place down the street could be farther than it looks. Definately wear comforatble shoes. As far as restaurants other than what's in the Mirage we tried a few. One of the best places we ate was Roy's Hawaiian Fustion near the Flamingo. They have great steak and seafood also very good desert. Grotto in the Golden Nugget had good Italian. Nine Fine Irishmen in New York, New York has great belly filling food such as shepherd's pie, burgers, fish &amp; chips. We took a tour of the Grand Canyon with Sundance Helicopters.They pick you up and drop you off at your hotel in a stretch limo. I highly recommend the champagne picnic tour. We flew over the Hoover Dam and Lake Mead and landed in the canyon for our picnic. It was great to see the landscape from the helicopter. On the way back we flew through the Strip past all the resorts. It was worth every penny. We drove to Red Rock Canyon one day. There is a spot in the sandstone quarry where you can climb to the top of Calico Tanks and see all of Las Vegas and just breath taking views. The drive to the canyon was only about 20 mins. The hike/climb was listed as moderate, however if you have any difficulties climbing stairs you may have trouble with this. Otherwise it's great.Oh, one after thought about the room itself; the doors slam easily. We made a point to not slam our door when it closes but I wish those around us would have made the same effort. We had a great time and I would highly recommend going to Vegas whether you enjoy gambling or not. We didn't gamble one cent and I'm already trying to figure out when we can go back.	
