Nov 14 2009 	Huge disappointment-deal was too good to be true!	I have traveled to Las Vegas a lot for business and pleasure. I was just here 7 weeks ago at MGM Grand. Because I stay and play so often, MGM Mirage sends me great offers for VIP room rates, etc. I decided to leave my baby boy with my hubby for 3 nights to take one of those great offers and celebrate my birthday a week late with a friend from Vegas. The offer from MGM Mirage includes offers from all of their properties, and the best value I got this time was with the Mirage. It was the only property that had a decent Saturday rate over fight weekend, and it looked like a nice place. I was surprised when I arrived and walked into the smallest, worst hotel room I've ever encountered in Vegas. I'd heard the rooms were redone a year ago, but this one is desperately in need of redecoration!The walk from the front desk to room was very long and as I'd arrived early (around noon) they had a room ready on the 6th floor, pretty low but I don't care much about the view having stayed in some of the best rooms in the city, so I took it. It IS a King room, a basic King, but it doesn't even have a small sitting area like MGM does. It has an ugly orange half/chair half/sofa? But nowhere to put your feet. The bathroom is the worst. It's smaller than any bathroom I've seen in Vegas. The bath amenities don't include any bath gel or body wash, and the soaps are so small that I'd run out after one bath. The old white tub was stained and right next to the toilet. The sink had no room for anything and the bathroom is claustraphobic.I am paying a resort fee of 15 dollars a day for what? MGM doesn't do that. They do have 2 bottles of water here as a welcome, I guess, part of the resort fee. But the worst thing I encountered is the smell! You know that awful disinfectant/too flowery scent that really old motels have? This room smells like the cheap ones my grandma used to get when I was a kid. They have an electronic mini-bar that looks like a fridge from the outside. I opened it and am sure I jostled something and will be accused of taking something. Luckily, everything is still there.After paying a resort fee, I am really upset that I had to pay for my internet! But I am happy to say I only need to spend one night here. I called VIP services at Mandalay Bay and they were able to get me a decent rate for Sunday and Monday nights. I cancelled tomorrow and Monday here, but they held $300 on my debit card that I won't get back for 30 days! I use that card at MGM all the time and they don't hold fees that long. I DID try to get another room here at Mirage, I wanted a King Tower or a small suite. I called front desk who put me in touch with the casino marketing, the ones who sent me the offer in the 1st place. I explained that the room was just not what I was used to and asked if I could get a different room. I was put on hold by a young lady who was very rude (she was talking to someone who gambles with MGM/Mirage and that's why I got the good room rates, so she should know better than to cop an attitude!) She said there were NO other rooms, which I know is not right as the people in front and to the sides of me were looking to choose different rooms. I offered to pay more for a suite, but they said if I wanted a suite I would have to pay regular rate. On a weekend, a FIGHT weekend, that is SO much more I can't even think about it.So here's the deal- they offer you a fantastic rate, knowing from your portfolio what types of rooms/suites you're used to. They give you the lowest type room available, knowing you will ask for a better room. Then they gouge you for more money. Nice way to treat MGM Mirage Players Club players! I came with money to play but damned if I will play here. Back to the management. They were unable to find me a better room for Sunday or Monday? The fight is tonight, I know that things are booked up. People are paying lots of money for rooms tonight. But tomorrow, they all leave, and Monday? Monday rates are very low. What the girl didn't know was that I knew that they had other rooms and suites available for Sunday and Monday- I was logged on to their website as I spoke to her! This room is the lowest type available, with the worst view. So they lied to me when I KNEW they had tower Kings available. Her story seemed to change, and I was quite confused. When she put me on hold to talk to her &quot;supervisor&quot; she was already in a huff.It seems like bait and switch to me, so for all those Player's Club people who get the MGM Mirage deals in the email- they're usually great deals. MGM, Mandalay and Bellagio have good deals and they have always been kind and respectful. I will NEVER stay at Mirage again, but I will take the other hotels up on their offers. I am grateful that the lady at VIP services at Mandalay was able to secure a nice room for me for a decent price for the next 2 nights. One night here won't kill me. I was a bit taken aback when I called down to say I was canceling my reservation tomorrow. They didn't even ask why, or could they fix it. AND, now that I think of it, the girl who checked me in didn't go over my Freeplay info. (I was supposed to get $25 towards table games or slots.) NOT impressed.	
Nov 14 2009 	perfect location for first time visitors	Hi there, this was the second time we visited Las Vegas. Our first time we stayed at the TI and we loved the location because it is in the Center of the Strip. Because of the location we booked this time the Mirage. Overall it is a perfect choice for first time visitors. We got a special rate 300$ for 5 nights and for this amount of money it was a perfect. We got a room with highway view :-( in the 17th floor. First they planned to give us a 2 queen bed room, but during check in we were able to change to a king size bed. Check in was friendly and fast, no problem. The room was large and clean. The room looked renovated. The only negative thing was the bathroom; it was very small compared to the room size.I can highly recommend the Mirage for first time Las Vegas visitors. I'm not sure if it is the best option for a hardcore gambler.	
Nov 13 2009 	Comfortable and very central if a little rowdy.	Have just returned from spending six nights at the Mirage (got a good room, car and flight deal with BA who now fly direct to LV). We checked in around 9.00pm and it was swift and efficient if a little charmless. We were offered a Strip view room on the non smoking 19th floor. The room was large with two double beds and in good condition, having been refurbished in an uncompromisingly modern style. It was smart and bold, dark woods, chrome, glass and faux leather but not what I'd describe as plush and luxurious. However, the beds were some of the most comfortable we have experienced, terrific. There was a 42&quot; flat screen HD TV and an iPod docking station. The complimentary daily bottled water was a nice touch too. There were traces of the old decor, the doors and wardrobes, and we wondered why they did not do a complete make over. It was the same with the bathroom. They are small, plain but functional. It looked like half the bathroom had been refurbished (nice vanity area), the other half left original. If you are going to replace all the taps with new modern ones, why leave the old shower head? It needed replacing, spraying everywhere except where needed! The light to the magnifying mirror did not work either. There were sufficient towels, if on the small side. The toiletries smelt great (lime) but there was no shower gel, just shampoo, conditioner and body lotion, and a rather unpleasant bar of exfoliating soap which dried out your skin. We bought some shower gel at a local pharmacy. House keeping was okay but we did find in plain view hair in the bathroom, probably belonging to the previous occupant when we checked in! And if you do get a Strip view room and intend to be in bed before midnight (!), get some ear plugs because the double glazing is poor (original) and the half hourly volcano show sounds like a freight train is heading for your room! The room was quiet otherwise and we heard very little noise from other guests in the corridor or adjoining rooms.We had breakfast several times at the buffet. There was very little waiting time and it ran very efficiently. The selection was mind boggling and it was all very good quality, with prompt, friendly service. We thought it good value too at just under 10GBP per head, even with a fairly poor £/$ exchange rate. In Europe you'd expect to pay nearly double for a spread like this. Over the weekend the breakfast buffet became 'brunch' and the price went up to about 13GBP a head but we failed to spot any difference from the week day buffet.The swimming pool area was beautiful with lush tropical landscaping and water falls. There was a massive free form pool, a smaller circular pool and an 'adults only' pool called 'Bare' in a secluded area away from the main pools. There were luxurious cabanas to rent which in the high season would be the best choice as the sun loungers were laid out in unimaginative row after row and in very close formation and it would be hell. We had breakfast in the Paradiso Cafe by the pool one morning which was very relaxing and comfortable but at almost twice the price as the buffet (for the same food) not worth it. The cooked breakfast arrived almost cold and the plastic crockery took the edge off the experience. The service here was a little lax too. We also tried the coffee shop for breakfast which had delicious muffins and danish pastries and did takeaway too.We dined at BLT (the gourmet burger restaurant) which was disappointingly ordinary and at the Carnegie Deli, which was excellent, massive portions and engaging staff. For all the dining outlets that did not require reservations, there were continual queues but they were fairly fast moving. We thought all the dining options had small seating capacities compared to other restaurants we visited during our stay.The free parking was good, the hike through the smokey casino to get to the guest lifts was not. The hotel shopping arcade was ordinary and the public areas lacked the WOW factor the other hotels had. The hotel location was brilliant, right in the thick of the action. Maybe this was why hotel was rather rowdy and occasionally rough, especially at night.We went to see Bette Midler - fab-u-lous! and Cirque de Soleil's KA at the MGM Grand. That was spectacular but we thought LOVE, which we saw at the Mirage three years ago was better. We also dined Michael Mina's Nobhill Tavern at the MGM Grand which was superb (fall tasting menu at $45 per head, a bargain), Wolfgang Puck's Postrio (restaurant, not cafe) at the Venetian which was pleasant but nothing special and the SW Steakhouse at the Wynn which was truly exceptional (remortgage to pay the bill - astronomical!).Check was also quick and efficient but more friendly. The Mirage is a top location but we think is getting left behind despite it's recent room upgrades, as more new hotels arrive and other older ones seem to be refurbishing, extending and improving to try and keep up. We stayed at the Bellagio last time which was fantastic, in another league and should we ever return, will head for the Wynn or the Palazzo or even the new Aria or Mandarin Oriental which are due to open in December.	
