Nov 7 2009	It's not just a mirage!	I stayed at the Mirage for 7 nights with 3 other people in late October. We mainly booked this hotel due to its great location and we were not disappointed as it’s in a prime location! Upon arriving within around 10 minutes we were checked in and on our way to the rooms. The only minor hiccup we had was the fact that when we booked we requested 2 rooms, each with 1 king-sized bed however, these were still being cleaned so we were given 2 rooms each with 2 queen sized beds, we didn't believe this to be an issue though. Each of the rooms was clean and spacious &amp; housekeeping came everyday and changed our towels and linen etc. Regarding the bathroom it was somewhat small however it was more than adequate. The view from our rooms was of the back of the hotel and looked out onto roads mainly but I didn't plan on sitting by the window anyway we were in Vegas after all! We found all the staff within the hotel to be very helpful, for instance one day we had a problem with one of our lamps and 5 minutes after informing reception someone was there fixing it. The facilities within the hotel were very good such as the shops, bars and restaurants which we ate at most nights. Some people have stated the restaurants are expensive but personally I didn’t believe this to be the case for the ones I experienced – BLT Burger, Carnegie Deli, California Pizza Kitchen &amp; Samba Brazilian Steakhouse. In British Pounds most meals worked out at around £15-20 including a drink which I think is pretty cheap. The only issue you may find when eating in the mirage is you pretty much have to queue for everything &amp; this can take 20m+ which I’d never experienced before but this seemed the norm on the strip. The bars in the mirage were also good such as the Rhumbar &amp; Revolution lounge both of which had a good atmosphere however, take plenty of $$$ if like me you don’t drink beer as you’ll be paying around $12-16 for a drink. While staying at the mirage we also went swimming and the pool was as good as it looks in the pictures definitely great for Vegas. We also visited the Secret Garden and Dolphin Habitat, which I must say was a let down as upon entering we were then told the Dolphins were having a rest day so we didn’t get to see much. Overall The Mirage may lack in over the top décor like some of the closer hotels however, it was a great place to stay in and we enjoyed it. The volcano was really good to see on a night and certainly different. I cannot really comment on the casino as I’m not really a gambler (lol) it always seemed busy though and the slots were certainly fun. As I’m sure you’ll know by now you need to walk through the casino to get to the rooms which I must admit became somewhat tiring towards the end of our stay but again from the other hotels I visited this was the norm. If I return to Vegas I would consider staying at the mirage again however I understand they’ve now introduced a resort fee so to be honest I’d more than likely upgrade and stay across the road at The Venetian or Wynn. A few tips:~Try see one of the Cirque du Soleil shows – we saw KA &amp; it was fantastic~Bally's (hotel) Jubilee show is also fantastic... true Vegas Glamour~Also the trips to the Grand Canyon are amazing but shop around for a good deal. ~Also DO NOT underestimate how big the strip is! I’m in my early twenties and the walking really took its toll on me and my feet! Try the shuttle buses or something as taxis are often at a stand still.	
