Oct 9 2009 	Vegas Revisited	Checked in at 10:30 am and assigned a room on the 14th floor overlooking the strip and the volcano. We last went to Vegas six years ago when we stayed at New York New York. This time we rented a car and drove up the strip and made a left into the parking area. The Mirage and TI share the same access for parking and you can enter and exit from both sides of the hotels. The room was nice and the casino typical of the strip. Later I drove to Lindo Michoacan restaurant for lunch. It is a nice, but dark, place and I thought it was pretty good. We saw the Beatles Love show and enjoyed the spectacle. The music was just OK to me. Not enough of the real Beatles sound, but still worth seeing. The next day we drove to a Denny's on West Tropicana and enjoyed the tranquil atmosphere. Then we hit the highway and headed to Hoover Dam. Just before you get to the dam there is pay parking to the left. We parked there and walked down and across. It was impressive as always. What really impressed me was the new bridge . The arch is complete and they are working (I think) on the span. They erected two large towers on each side of the canyon and ran heavy cable which supports two cranes used to bring the materials and parts to the span. It is an interesting engineering feat. Later we drove to Ellis Island to try the food, I had the famous steak special and the wife tried the fried fish. We were happy with the food and service. We went back the next day and I tried another dish that I liked even though I was tempted to try the steak again. I thought I had my gambling system down (I only play craps) so I talked my wife into playing craps instead of the slots. I told her to play the pass line and she did, but she added her own touch so I let her learn the hard way I guess. I began with a hundred and she with fifty. I left with nothing and she with a hundred and sixty five. This was at the Main Street Hotel and Casino. You can park for three dollars and get it back inside the casino. We wanted to try the buffet and the omelet guy put on a good show. Then we walked down to Fremont Street and checked out old Vegas. We really enjoyed being off the main strip this time. We decided to play craps again while there so I changed a hundred and she fifty. I left with nothing and she with a hundred and 10 dollars. I really enjoyed watching her get into the game and leave a winner. What more could you ask for? The other highlight of our trip was seeing the Jersey Boys show. This is more of a stage production which differs from the Cirque du Solei shows. It was entertaining and interesting to hear the story of Frankie Valli. Both times we were in the last row, but still worth it. All in all a great three days and nights in Vegas.	
