Oct 8 2009 	Many diasppointments with the Mirage	We stayed at The Mirage Sept 30- Oct 3. This was the second part of a 6 night stay that included Mandalay Bay (separate review). Unfortunately, there were not many highlights of this part of our stay. We got to the Mirage about 1:30 and approached the check-in desk. We were told that our room would not be ready for three hours and that was with a rush on it. We were a little surprised as we were checking in on a Wednesday, not a particularly busy day I thought. We dropped off our luggage with the bell hop and went to an area around the sports betting room and waited till about 4. Went back to see if our room was ready and were told no, not yet. I asked her why it took so long to clean a room. She said it was because it was a Tower Suite, it took longer; but 3 hours? I asked her is she had any other Tower suites available (as we requested a non-smoking) and I was amazed that they did have a smoking one available. I asked why, if I was already here, you would not clean the room I had requested before the smoking rooms. No real answer. I then asked if the smoking room would have a strong smoke odor and her reply was “. . . well they have been smoking in them for 20 years, so what do you think?” I asked for an upgrade to a Penthouse Suite, or some resort credit for having to wait since check-in is supposed to be at 3 and it was 4:30 by now; again she said that she could not. I tried to call my travel agent, but with the time change, they were closed for the day. So we waited about 15 more minute and then the room was ready.We had room A-55, a Tower Suite, which you access through private elevators for floors A-E. This floor is designated non-smoking, but the hallway still smelled like old cigar smoke. The room itself had no smell. The double doors to the room shook every time someone else opened or closed their door and did not feel too secure. The room itself was very outdated and extremely worn. It has the look I would describe as Golden Girls. Everything was very bright and had a whitewashed look from the late 80’s. I was expecting the room to be remodeled since I had heard that most other rooms had been but was surprised to hear from the bellman, which was very nice, that they stopped remodeling on the 25 floor. All their suites are above that floor and all of us could not understand why you would not renovate your better rooms first. The room itself was clean, but felt dirty as everything was old and worn. There was a huge armoire with the TV, not even a flat screen, and hodge-podge stereo equipment. Fabric on the chairs and sofas was old and felt kind of gross to sit on. The dining table had an ugly chandelier above it. The wet bar did have a separate fridge, but the tiles were a light marble and the sink was bright brass. The bathroom had 2 walls of mirrors and a huge vanity area that was unappealing. There was a nice, large closet and chest for clothes. The separate toilet and bidet room also had a mirrored wall in it that I found somewhat gross. The bedroom had a cabinet at the end of the bed where a TV would pop out, but ours was stuck up, again another old tube TV. Bed was nice and comfortable. The view was only partially of the strip, but even that view was hard to see at the hotel had put a wrap over the top 5 floor windows advertising their Beatles, Love, show. It is very hard to see out of the windows as the wrap only has tiny holes to look through. Also one of the outer panes of glass was cracked.The hotel itself has an old vibe and did not seem to be modern at all. The casino was dark and smokey with low ceilings, not what we have witnessed at other hotels in Vegas. It was a very long way to get from the check-in to the elevators. Trudging through the casino with you luggage is not that fun. We did not have that problem at Mandalay Bay. While the pool area is very nice with large pools and waterfalls, there is too many tall trees that shade much of the lounge chairs. If you want the sun, you will need to move often or keep turning you chair.The last night we were there we went to bed early as we had an early flight. There was a concert poolside to celebrate their 20th anniversary. The concert started at 10pm and went to 1:30am with music so loud that stuff in the room was shaking and we were on the 26th floor. So we did not get much sleep that night and had a long day to get back home. Other then the nice location on the strip, we would never stay there again. There were too many disappointments and very few bright spots of this hotel. Maybe it was because we had a great time at Mandalay Bay before and our expectations were high from that or it is just a property that needs some improvement on its staff and rooms.	
