Sep 29 2009 	Cannot be beaten	Checked in on the 7th Sept 09 around 6pm and the experience was very quick and efficient. Only one person in front of us and they had plenty of reception staff. I had read a couple of reviews about the rooms having small bathrooms which concerned me a little so as we checked in I mentioned that we were getting married whilst we were there so would like a room with a big bathroom to get ready.. It was no problem at all. We were given a huge room on the 25th floor with fantastic views of the pool, dolphins and strip. ..and the bathroom was amazing (His and hers sinks, jacuzzi bath and huge separate shower cubicle. If this hotel room was in England, it would definitely be a 5 star!! The beds and pillows were the best we have ever experienced which makes them very difficult to drag yourself out of!! Floors 24 &amp; 25 have separate elevators so getting up and down to our room was a breeze. They sent up a bottle of champagne the night before we got married which was an excellent touch. The hotel looks fantastic. There is a massive fish tank along the reception wall and the Atrium is beautiful. The Casio was huge but not as big as some we saw (which is not a bad thing). We expected it to be a bit smokey for us and we kind of got used to the smoking ban in the UK but it was not a problem at all. Pool looked amazing but very busy. We didn’t use it as didn’t have time but we had a walk around and it looked fab. You have to very intimate with your fellow sunbathers as all the sunbeds were in rows and touching each other (I think that may have bothered me). Location The hotels location is perfect. It was right in the heart of the action in the centre of the strip. All our favourite hotels were within walking distance so it really was perfect. Food/Drink/Entertainment You really could have stayed for a month and have eaten at all the places available to eat. We didn’t eat here much mainly because we were out and about most of the week..All the restaurants looked fantastic and they were always buzzing with lots of people. We used the Carnegie Deli a couple of times for breakfast which was lovely. We didn’t try the buffet as portions out there are big enough without having the option to eat as much as you can! The restaurants are pretty expensive but no more than anywhere else in Vegas. For people on a budget (as we were) there is Denny’s (fab for breakfast)and McDonalds across the road and most hotels have food courts (Try Nathans hotdogs if you get chance) We loved the sports bar which we sat in a few evenings watching the world go by and the Revolution bar was great too. We went to see the Beatles “Love” show on Saturday night which was pretty good. Again, very expensive but if you ask for discount it makes it more reasonable. They knocked us 40% off and said they give discount to anyone that asks. They also give you a couple of vouchers for a free drink in the Revolution bar. Would have loved to have seen Terry Fator but didn’t have the spare bucks unfortunately. All in all we made the perfect choice here. We walked around most of the other Casino Hotels and thought we had picked the best one for price, location, amenities and atmosphere. There were prettier and more lavish hotels like the Encore/Bellagio etc but I’m not sure we would have felt so much at home at these places. Stay here, you will not be disappointed!! Vegas Recommendations:- Grand Canyon - Grand Adventures did a brilliant tour. Perfect!! Weddings – Little Chapel of the flowers. Again perfect from start to finish. Great afternoon in the bar – Go see Big Elvis at Bill’s Gambling Hall. Great entertainment and the bar is one of the cheapest in Vegas!!	
Sep 29 2009	A good stay	I stayed at the Mirage during the same period last year and LOVED it. I still like it after this stay but I definately saw some changes compared to last year. The stay was much cheaper this year due to some deals that I was able to get online mainly I think because of the recession in the US. I think this recession probably caused some cutbacks in the hotels as well ( I am Canadian and we were not hit as badly by the recession as our nieghbors to the south so I can only guess at this based on what I have seen in the news and from my experience). We landed early at 10:30 am and were exhausted from the early flight and time change so we decided to try to get into our room at this time and we were very relieved when we were able to do this. We got the room on a deal as I said so we didn't care that it was on the 8th floor and had a view of the trump and not much else not a big deal to us. I went to take a shower and realized after getting in that the inside shower curtain was caked with what i sincerely hope was mold and not something more disgusting on the inside of it--that was a big deal to us, when I got out of the shower I grabbed a towel and it was covered in a mysterious brown stain that I also didn't want to think too much about. I know it was washed but it still doesn't seem right to leave that for a guest to use. In all fairness we didnt' have anything but clean towels for the rest of the stay and we called housekeeping and asked for a new shower curtain the next day which of course they said they were happy to do I left a note for the maid as a reminder with an extra tip to ensure that it would get done and it did. The makeup mirror in the bathroom was broken and the alarm clock by the beds wouldn't light up. All minor things but I was surprised because all of these rooms were only remodeled last year and when I was there after the renovation everything was high quality and pristine and now i can't help but wonder if some of the renovations were done too cheaply as they don't seem to be holding up well. Overall minor problems nothing that would wreck my vacation or stay I will stay at the mirage again as the location and the price really can't be beat.	
