Sep 14 2009	Felt Like a High Roller!	It had been over 7 years since I had last been to Vegas, and about 5 for my parents, so we decided to take a trip to celebrate their wedding anniversary in early August. After staying on the now-depressing north end of the Strip the last several times we were there, we decided to stay at the Mirage.I'm not exactly a swanky person myself, but I appreciated the swankiness of the Mirage. I booked a standard King Room for myself. It was on the 11th floor and had a wonderful view of the expressway and the mountains. I wasn't looking for a spectacular view, so I was satisfied. The room was cool. The bathroom is small, but well appointed. I didn't plan on having a party in the bathroom. The Aqua Lime bath products are great.All of my dining experiences were great. The Caribe Cafe is expensive, but the food was very good. Ate there for breakfast a few times and a dinner once. Also ate at BLT Burger once. Yes, it's almost $20 for a burger and fries, but it was well worth it for the experience. There is one way around the &quot;not enough chairs around the pool&quot; problem... rent a cabana. If you split the cost amongst several people, it is well worth it. Spent the entire day at the pool the day before we left. There is refrigerator stocked with soda, a fresh fruit plate and a cheese and cracker plate. The waitstaff comes by every 30 minutes or so to see if you needed anything. It was a great experience.I thought the casino was great. I did well gambling, so I guess that made it all the better. The MGM Mirage Player's Club was also generous to me (I'm not a high roller by any means, but I actually got something comped for the first time ever - yay me!). If you do any gambling at all, make sure you sign up for the Player's Club.The saddest part of the trip was leaving. I'd definitely stay at the Mirage again.	
