Sep 10 2009 	Beyond Expectations!	My friends and I stayed at the Mirage for 5 nights at the beginning of September. We arrived in Las Vegas late in the evening so luckily we did not encounter any line-up at all at the check-in counter. The staff at the check in counter were very friendly and set our vacation off on the right foot. We were checking into two separate rooms and received a complimentary upgrade on both of them. Both rooms were on the 24th floor, access via a private elevator. One room over looked the volcano while the other room was given a beautiful view of the mountains to the West (we could see Red Rock Canyon from the room).Housekeeping kept my room in great condition the entire time. They were very quick and efficient. I would spend my mornings down at the pool and by lunch time, housekeeping had already done their round though the room.The pool does get busy very quickly at the Mirage, but considering how beautiful the pool is, its business is not a surprise at all. Finding a set of 4 chairs in the morning was never a problem. Most people I observed getting frustrated over chair numbers seemed to expect sun shining down on their chair at that very moment; rather than realize that the sun moves and soon enough the available shaded chairs would be in direct sunlight. The chair-side service at the pool was very quick and the girls were always very friendly. The prices for drinks and food at the pool were not as bad as they could be (considering this is Las Vegas and you are receiving service right to your chair at a gorgeous pool). The only downside to the pool at the Mirage is that it has now forced me to have a new standard for all pools I go to. If a pool doesn’t have two waterfalls, it just may not be worth visiting. (haha)I did not gamble much at the casino as the table minimums were a bit out of my range. I like how the casino is laid out as it feels more spread out than other casinos.We ate at California Pizza Kitchen, BLT Burger, and the buffet. C.P.K. was an alright meal, but nothing spectacular. The pizza was a little disappointing coming from a kitchen who is specializing in pizza. There was not much difference in the pizza from this kitchen than from any family chain restaurant. BLT Burger was fantastic. The Kobe Beef sliders were brilliantly done and the onion rings were light and crunch. The highlight of our dining at The Mirage was the buffet. We lucked out here. The day we chose to try the buffet, the price was a little higher than usual but it included free, unlimited champagne and orange juice. Where is Las Vegas do you get free, unlimited and copious amounts of alcohol? I think the food was good at the buffet too.....?I had been anticipating this trip for months and was worried that I may had developed too high of expectations for The Mirage. I am happy to say that The Mirage performed way beyond all of my expectations. It will not be a hard decision to return to the Mirage in the near future. I am looking forward to my next visit already.	
Sep 10 2009 	Most beautiful lobby tropical atrium and tropical grounds!	We stayed at the Mirage August 25-28, 2009. After much searching we chose the Mirage and were not disappointed. Of all the resorts we saw, we loved the Mirage the most because of the beautiful tropical atrium that greets you when you walk in and the gorgeous tropical pool area and grounds! The beds were extremely comfortable and the rooms were clean with good service. I would suggest not staying in a west facing room in the summer as we could never get our room below 70-75 degrees! We tried to switch rooms, but that one was hotter. It was 106 outside. Tip: Turn on your AC as low as it goes in the morning or right when you get there before you go out so your room is comfortable when you get back in. We also blocked our door open when we were there in the day time and that helped as the hallway was cooler than our room. Food is very expensive everywhere on the strip. It would pay to pay to bring an extra suitcase on the plane with snacks and bottled water as bottled water is $6. Also, stop at Walgreens on the strip the first day you are there and stock up with water and snacks. It will save you tons! Also, across the street from the Mirage is a 4Bs and a little Subway in a casino that had slightly more reasonable meals for a light lunch. Save up and don't miss the Buffet at the Wynn within walking distance. Go about 2:45 p.m. to 3:00 and pay lunch price and they put out the evening dinner food about 3:30 so you can also enjoy crab and prime rib for the same cost as the lunch meal. It is about $28. It jumps to like $38 after 3:30 and you can stay. AVOID the Criss Angel Believe Show at ALL COSTS!!!! We are even a fan of his and it was HORRIBLE! He just talks most of the time, has dancing people in bunny costumes and loud music. He does like 3 or 4 lame illusions of levitating while covered in smoke! Watch him on t.v. Don't waste $100 to go see this disaster!!! DO GO SEE CIRQUE DU SOLEILL &quot;O&quot; Show at the Bellagio!! It was truly amazing! The stage turns into a lake and has lots of acrobatics and dancing! It is more mellow, but amazing! Even my husband and twenty year old sons liked it. We also wish we would have gone to see Terry Fator Venturliquist rather than Criss Angel. We wouldn't have wasted our money. Enjoyed the mirage and Vegas, but be prepared to spend a lot of money on food and drinks!	
