Aug 31 2009 	OVERALL GOOD SOME FLAWS	After staying at Harrah's and TI, I decided to splurge and try the Mirage. I will try to be as honest as I know how. This will be lengthy.I booked the flight and room directly through the Mirage website and had no problems whatsoever. My stay was from 8/24 to 8/29.I arrived at 1:30 P.M. The room was not ready. They told me to check back at 3:00 and asked for my cell phone number in case something came up earlier. I went back at 3:00 and my room was still not ready, but I was offered the room right next door, which I accepted. Everyone at the desk was very friendly and courteous.I went to the Impulse store and bought 2 beers to take up to the room. I went to the room and called the Bell Desk. I went and got some ice and before I opened the first bottle of beer, I heard a knock at the door and it was the Bell Man! Astonishing! I believe his name was Tom and he was the friendliest guy in the world. He showed where everything was and how everything worked. He was so funny, I tipped him a $10 instead of the normal $5.I unpacked, took in the view, put my iPod in the handy iPod station and relaxed with my beers. I was thrilled with the Strip view of the Venetian, Harrah's, Volcano, the distant mountains and the planes coming in for a landing.The room, upon first glance, was very nice. I was in 24054, so I guess this is one of the unrenovated rooms, because I thought the bathroom was huge. There was a very comfortable king-sized bed and a great tv. There were plenty of outlets for your electronic doodads.Housekeeping on Tuesday and Wednesday was perfect. It slipped a bit on Thursday. It was non-existent on Friday. I vacated the room from 8:00 A.M. to well after 2:00 P.M. (including a brief stop to change for the pool). I called down and was told that the maids were still at lunch. Well, I was ready to relax in the room before dinner and a show and was not going to leave. A maid did come by a little later, but I told her just to give me soap and clean towels. I expect a little more from a 4-star hotel. No tip, sorry!I also reported on Thursday that I had accidentally pulled up too far on the sink plunger and it came loose from the thing that makes it go up and down. I could have fixed it myself in 30 seconds if I had a flashlight. I reported it right away, but no one ever showed to fix it. There was also some ground in chewing gum on the bathroom tile, directly in my line of sight while I was sitting on the can. To the left of that was a red stain which may or may not have been blood. The towel rack on the right sink was bent where someone had slammed a door into it. The shower was either full blast or nothing. I never used the tub or the spa.The Pool. It is absolutely beautiful, with waterfalls, palms and eucalyptus and all of the other landscaping. The lounge chair situation is just plain silly. I witnessed some of the most incredible scenes of greed and selfishness that could be imagined. People had chairs reserved for buddies all over the entire pool area. I would say by estimation that 70% of the chairs were unoccupied, but had towels on them. Discounting those people actually in the pool, I would say that 25% of the chairs were being reserved. I came very close one day to taking a pair of silver sandals and throwing them into the pool. People were wandering all over looking for chairs. I did score a chair one day by watching who was leaving and hustling to snag the chair. This was after 2 hours of sitting by the side of the pool with my stuff on a rock. Another day, I came out after 2:00 P.M. and got one fairly quickly, but the people around me gave me dirty looks like I was some sort of alien from outer space. One middle aged lady with a deep south accent actually looked at me and curled her lip!!! The third time I went, on Friday, with all of the SoCal knuckleheads showing up, I didn't expect to get a chair and I didn't. Just grabbed a rock for my stuff and sat on the edge of the pool. The staff did go around and start picking towels off of unoccupied chairs from time to time. On a good note, Monica from Chicago was a good and attentive pool waitress. The bar at the pool was very nice.Shows. I saw the Beatles Love show (2nd time) and Terry Fator. I liked the fact that Terry paid tribute to us military veterans. He puts on a good show. My seat was terrible however. It was way off to the left and should have been discounted as an obstructed view seat. I enjoyed the show, but would probably not see it again. The Beatles Cirque du Soleil was great again. You can't go wrong with this show. The seat was perfect. I booked both seats through the hotel.Dining. Being a solo, I'm sheepish about going to the fancy places. I did eat at BLT Burger, California Pizza Kitchen and Carnegie Deli.BLT - Great burger! It should be for what they charge. Basic burger with 2 extra toppings, fries and a microbrew, $33 including the tip. I honestly can say that I have had better fries at Burger King. Service was good.CPK - I had two pasta meals here. Service was incredible! Jim and Joe at the bar are awesome! Great service, good meal!Carnegie Deli - I ate breakfast here twice. No complaints other than that I never got a refill on my coffee. The food was very good.Cravings - I went here once for breakfast. I was seated so far away from the serving lines that my food was cold by the time I got back to my table. This was my second time here and I'm still waiting for my first good experience. Gambling - The dealers were pretty decent. Vaughn was unintentionally funny with his offbeat theories. Most of them tried to make it fun. I was a little taken aback by one Hispanic lady who kept a running conversation in Spanish going with other Hispanic patrons. I'm not mad at her though, because she dealt me a straight flush in 3 Card Poker. I never got into my favorite game, Craps, because of the high minimums. There should always be one $5 table going. This is the most fun game to play, but at $10 and $15 minimums, I would have had to buy in at $200 to play my style of game. Too much for me. I did okay at slots. The Sports Book is a nice place to relax and throw down some baseball bets. I did not try the Poker Room. These people never seem like they are having any fun.Bars - I have no complaints about any of the bars.Nightclubs - The Mirage has Jet and Revolution. I'm too old for this stuff, but the girls in line all looked fabulous. If I were only 25 and rich!Checkout on Friday was flawless. The Desk staff is to be commended!Overall, I enjoyed my stay and would recommend it to others, but you need to look past tne minor flaws. The pool thing is just ridiculous. One solution would be to charge $5 for a lounge chair. And tightening security would help as well, since I'm positive this pool gets invaded by people from other hotels.I would stay here again, when all is said and done. The location and the grounds are just perfect.	
Aug 31 2009 	Resort with no coffee shop - STUPID	At the cost of the guest, The Mirage has decided to increase their bottom line by closing their 24/7 coffee shop &amp; restaurant, &quot;Caribe&quot;. They have instructed their staff to now direct guests to &quot;Carnegie Deli&quot; which serves only NY deli style food, in massive portions that can only be described as ridiculously wasteful...albeit tasty. Their breakfast offerings are primarily 3-egg omelets; not much else. And the seating capacity is considerably less than the much larger &quot;Caribe&quot; - creating a long wait for much needed morning caffeine. The resort has added a Starbucks, but in doing so, closed one of their other two coffee bars; long lines await the morning customer. By reducing the breakfast options, The Mirage is forcing their guests to leave the resort and risk them not returning to their gaming floor. We became regular morning customers at Treasure Island's 24-hour restaurant; a short tram ride to the next-door property. We have been long-time fans and guests of The Mirage, but in light of their recent business decision we are considering selecting a new favorite hotel for our semi-annual trips to Vegas.	
