Aug 28 2009 	Great hotel/awesome location!	We checked in on Aug. 23. I had booked for $70/night, 2 standard view rooms, one for myself and my husband and one for my 2 daughters, ages 13 and 10. We advised that we were there for our anniversary and were promptly upgraded to a strip view room. We were also told that while they could not put our daughters room side by side with us, that they would only be 5 rooms away. Imagine our surprise when we realized room 17037 and 17047 were not a few doors down, but in a whole other wing. We went and spoke to the front desk again and they moved our children to right across from us with no problem. The rooms are very sleek and art-deco in design. Not my personal taste, but very nicely done. We had a great view of the strip and of the volcano. Now for the interesting part, the pool. They have an awesome pool, very large with waterfalls and tons of chairs all around. I'm glad we checked in on a Sunday because apparently it wasn't crowded, so I was told. Well, when I went to get my coffee downstairs on Monday a.m. at 7:30, there was already quite a line up for the pool. There is a large sign at the front saying no reserving of pool chairs, but that sign really didn't matter. My husband and I went for a quick walk and returned at 8:30 to find the pool open and only a scant few chairs left. We quickly grabbed 4 together and put out towels and some personal items, i.e., magazines to reserve the chairs. We really didn't get the kids and us together down to the pool until about 10:00 and everything was still there. For the rest of the time we were there, we did the same thing, getting on line earlier and earlier each day so that I could get some chairs in shade. The key is to not only leave towels on the chairs, but some sort of personal item, i.e., a beach bag, 1/2 cup coffee or soda, lotion, etc. It worked fine, but I still can't get over waiting on that stupid line for the pool. And every chair was taken by 9:00 a.m. At that time, there were people milling around looking for chairs with none to be found.We used the spa - I had a great facial. Lovely spa area and would use it again. Casino is smallish but not bad. Loved the area, right central to everything, all the other great hotels and lots of shopping.We used the valet service for our car twice and our car was promptly brought to us. We called from the room and by the time we got downstairs, the car was there. Very friendly valet people. All in all a great trip. The kids had a blast as well at the pool and at some of the other hotels that had game rooms. Unfortunately Mirage doesn't have a game room. That would be the only thing I missed there and would've made it a bit easier. We also saw the Terry Fator show. Awesome!!! Great for kids as well.	
Aug 27 2009 	Fabulous Hotel - Ignore Bad Reviews!!	My boyfriend and I stayed at the Mirage a couple weeks ago and it was fantastic!!! I don't know what some people are talking about when they say the bathrooms are small! Ours had his and hers sinks, a shower and a tub - it was HUGE! (See pictures). I understand that they are still undergoing renovations on some of the rooms, but if you get assigned a room, and the bathroom does not look like the one pictured - simply ask to be moved to one of the newly renovated rooms. No offense, but you'd think a seasoned Vegas visitor would know this. The bed was comfy and the decor was nice and modern. There was a huge TV as well, but we probably spent 5 minutes total watching it.I honestly can't say one bad thing about the Mirage. We're already planning a trip back in April and we won't stay anywhere else. The pool is fantastic - it's a good size (that being huge) and the waterfalls are beautiful. People do get up and reserve lounge chairs at 8:00am, but I'm pretty sure you'll find this happens at every hotel on the strip. I actually got yelled at by an angry man for saving my boyfriend a lounge chair, but whatever - not the Mirage's fault that jerks stay there.We ate at Stack in the hotel and it was the best dinner we had all week. Definitely try their $29.99 per person Summer Tasting menu. Huge delicious portions. We also ate at California Pizza Kitchen which is always a winner in my book.We saw both shows at the Mirage. Terry Fator was a pretty good show, but LOVE was fantastic! I highly recommended it. I would give the Mirage 6-stars if I could. Good location, great rooms, amazing pool.	
Aug 26 2009 	Mirage Vacation	We just returned from a week long stay at the Mirage (which we got a great deal through Westjet Vacations that included free show tickets). This being my 3rd time in Vegas, and my husbands 1st. Check InWe arrived in Vegas just before noon and thought we'd try getting our room early. Unfortunately, the lady who served us at the desk was not very pleasant. Asked if there were any complimentary upgrades for a tower room, but was denied. Not a big deal, as my next request for a high floor with a view was granted. Was offered a volcano view, or a south strip/pool view. I love looking down the strip, so we were able to see the south strip, the pool and the mountains. King bed, non smoking as per our reservation. Room was not ready early, so we checked our bags with the bell desk and headed for lunch and viewed the Dolphin Habitat.RoomWe had a room on the 18th floor, with a king bed. The new decor is just how it looks in all of the website pictures. Daily maidservice was great, and if we needed anything, we just left a note requesting it (leaving a tip always goes a long way). As others have said, the bathroom is a bit small, but nothing to complain about. Nice flat screen tv, black out curtains are great for sleeping in and plenty of closet and drawer space. There is also a small table/desk, which works out perfect for a quick room service treat or if you have your laptop with you. I also liked that there are various lights around the room in the different areas.My only down point, was that you could hear everything from the hallway and rooms next door. If you are a light sleeper, this may be bothersome, but wasn't a big issue for us.Casino and Security/StaffThe casino seems to always be a buzz with lots of people. We did not play much here as the slots were tight. There were always a lot of staff maintaining public areas. At no time did we feel unsafe in the casino or on the Mirage property. Security seemed to have a good presence, and checked room keys at the elevators at night. Security also responded promptly to our call of extremely rowdy neighbours across the hall, who were running around naked and yelling at 5am. Bell staff was very effecient and friendly.FoodWe had lunch at the Cravings Buffet and I was quite disappointed. Needless to say we didn't eat there at all the rest of the trip. We did have great meal at California Pizza Chicken. As a side note, Caribe Cafe has closed. BLT burger has great burgers and shakes, if you don't mind spending around $20 on a combo meal. We also ordered room service breakfast twice and it was always delivered on time, or earlier than they had said. I don't mind paying a couple extra dollars when you don't feel like leaving the room after a late night out.PoolAlthough we did not spend anytime in the pool, it is a beautiful area with the waterfalls and offers shaded areas. Of course it can get very busy, and people often line up before it opens to get the best choice of loungers. It was about 110 degrees everyday, too hot for me to lay out in the sun.OthersLove using the free tram to Teasure Island. I believe it runs from 9am to midnight.Check out the beautiful atruim and the giant fish tank behind reception.Dolphin Habitat will cost you $15 per person. I've enjoyed it each time, especially to see how much the baby dolphin and leopard cub have grown since my last visits.Volcano out front erupts nightly.People rave about the show &quot;Love&quot;. Although we did not see the show, it is neat to check out the theatre area. The nightclubs always seem busy, but we didn't check them out. Stop for your refills at Rumbar on your large slushy drinks.Vegas Food InfoWe really enjoyed the Treasure Island buffet (based on what you get for the pricepoint and quality). The staff even remembered me from my previous visit in March.We had the best breakfast at the Grand Lux Cafe (Venetian). My favourite on the strip for lunch is Mon Ami Gabi (Paris). We splurged on a meal at Wolfgang Puck's Bar and Grill at the MGM before seeing a show. By far the best meal we have eaten.Check out Jean Phillipe's desserts at the Bellagio (as well as his chocolate fountain).Overall we had a great stay at the Mirage. If the price was right, I would definitely stay again.	
Aug 25 2009 	Rooms are tranquil getaway from casino chaos.	I traveled with two 14 year olds and got a room with 2 queen beds and a rollaway. Before booking on line, I called directly and asked three times to be sure that the extra person fee ($30/night) would include a rollaway. When I called back to confirm a rollaway, I was told it would be an extra expense (another $30/night). When I explained I called before booking, they went ahead and gave me the rollaway at no extra cost. Things I thought we would appreciate: The pool got such great reviews, I thought it would be something the kids would enjoy. They didn't use it once, though appreciated looking at it. Even from our 3rd floor, relatively near the elevators room, the pool was quite a trek to get to. Things we actually appreciated: Proximity to the Venetian. The kids could walk across the street to the Venetian, which is where my son really wanted to stay but I didn't want the extra expense. Frankly, I liked that they had to go out in the sunshine and get a little fresh air to get to the Venetian. I'm not sure they would have so willingly gone outside if we had stayed there. In fact the location was just all around good. Drawbacks: The only drawbacks to the Mirage are the same as those for all the massive casino hotels--there are just too many people there. And we went in August which I understand is not the busy season. That said, the people are largely in the casino and public areas. The hotel corredors and rooms were peaceful and quiet. Service: I really never want much in the way of &quot;service&quot; from a hotel. We called for extra towels once and they were delivered quickly. The people at the concierge desk were moderately helpful and always polite. The check in staff was pleasant and efficient--though I specifically arranged travel to avoid the busiest times. For example, I booked the hotel room for the final day of our stay even though we wouldn't spend the night. It just makes for an easier trip. Ordinary check in and check out times are just awful, regardless of where you are. We toured several hotels around 11 a.m. and they are just zoos.In the hotel we ate once at each of the following: Cravings--was fine. As with many buffets it is heavy on the high-starch, greasy foods. Some simple things, like egg-drip soup, were badly done. Others, like tomato soup, were well done. I primarily had prime rib and shrimp cocktail with salad and some sweet potatoes. All that was good, as were the bread pudding (mostly a custard, very little bread) and coconut macaroons. The kids enjoyed the pizza. Roasted Bean--as a Starbucks devotee I rarely try other coffee shops, but this one was well worth it, even better--at least in some respects--than Starbucks. The croissant was especially good--just a good plain butter croissant. The simplest things are often the hardest to pull off. And the coffee is extremely good and extremely strong without that faint burnt taste that some dark roasts have. Carnegie Deli: The sandwiches are about $20 each and ridiculously large, but they were a hit and when most dinner places were overcrowded it was a relatively quick way to have a good dinner back in the room. Seven layer choc. cake also a hit. I would recommend this hotel for people who are trying to balance what they want against what their kids want. If I were not going with kids, I'd stay further out of town.	
