Aug 20 2009 	Mirage Zoo- still fun but smaller now	We were saddened on our latest trip to Vegas, to find that many of the Las Vegas attractions that appeal to children, have been removed. One of these is the white tiger pool at the Mirage Hotel &amp; Casino. This used to be conveniently located in one of the main hallways, and was a great, free attraction for families. Whenever we visited, this attraction was packed with people enjoying the view of a big white tiger in a gorgeous blue pool with waterfalls and amazingly colorful tile work. Now it has been replaced with yet another restaurant.  We still enjoyed the large aquarium behind the front desk, and the pretty bit of indoor jungle just inside the front doors. And the little zoo is still there to enjoy - which we did. To anyone who has been to a lot of the big zoos of the world, be warned: It is small. But we like it.	
Aug 20 2009 	Contemporary Rooms Great Location Excellent Value	We booked two rooms for two nights at the Mirage in August to celebrate my dad's 60th birthday. My husband and I had stayed at the Bellagio in May, and were really disappointed, so I wasn't sure what to expect from a lesser-rated property like the Mirage (we chose it because we had tickets to see The Beatles Love). From the moment we set foot in the lobby, we were treated wonderfully. The check-in lines were long, but not as long as the Bellagio and the woman who checked us in did so very fast. We stayed on the 23rd floor, room 066, and loved the view of the Strip (booked on the Mirage Web site for only $104 per night). The room was spacious and very modern - gorgeous flat screen TV in front of the very comfy bed. Two complaints: First, the bathroom. It was small and the bathtub filled up when we took a shower. (The bathrooms at the Bellagio are definitely nicer.) The room was also a bit noisy - lots of slamming doors late at night and early (by Vegas standards) maid service. The pool area was absolutely fabulous - again, much better than the Bellagio. Finding a chair at noon was difficult, even on a Monday, but we managed. The great music playing at the pool drowns out the steady drone of helicopters that constantly seem to circle the Strip. Enjoyed a great lunch and very friendly service at the Carnegie Deli, and we were thrilled to find an actual Starbucks on property (even if the price of a muffin is four times that of a regular Starbucks). We tried to get into Jet (the nightclub), but, after standing in line for an hour and with at least another hour to go, we decided to skip it this time. The breakfast buffet is wonderful, too. Unfortunately, the drinks at the pool and the Revolution Lounge are quite overpriced. While I wouldn't stay at the Bellagio again (overpriced, out dated, not 5-star service), I am definitely looking forward to returning to the Mirage.	
