Aug 14 2009 	Ok but it has to be better in Vegas	My husband and I stayed three nights. We arrived a little past midnight. My husband checked in and was told we have to go to a smoking room since all of the non smoking rooms were already taken, even though I requested a non-smoking room when reservations made in June. He was told that there were no other rooms that the hotel was totally booked up. We went to the room and the smell of stale smoke made me sick, even the bed pillows smelling like an ashtray. I called the front desk and we were moved to a room that I originally requested (king, non-smoking). The bed was comfy but the bathroom was way too small. The second room was very clean, the first smoking room had a bobby pin on the floor in the bathroom and hair all in the tub. We went by the concerige desk the next day for any recommendations on shows or any entertainment ideas, the girl just gave us a list of all the shows and acted like she was annoyed with the question. We asked about the monorail and she again handed us a brochure. Totally not helpful. Pool was way too crowded with all the chairs. All facilities (salon, food, store) were all over priced for the quality. All staff encountered were borderline indifferent/rude with the exception of one poolside waitress. She was very nice. It's a mediocre hotel, for the money the strip has better to offer.	
Aug 14 2009 	I Love Vegas	My husband was attending a conference June 4-7 and I decided to tag along. We arrived to long lines and manual check-ins as the whole MGM-Mirage computer system had apparently crashed--even some of the slot machines were out of service! Staff did the best they could and remained polite and professional. Check-in was long and painful as staff had to manually look up reservations and phone for credit info; and after that, there was a wait for keys to be programmed. Through it all though, we did get a room that accounted for the few requests we had (higher floor, non-smoking, king bed). Joy was to be short-lived though as we discovered that the shower was broken, in that when turned on, a stream of water would shoot out the side and accoss the bathroom hitting the mirror, pretty much soaking everthing on the counter (and eventually, the floor). Not wanting to bother front desk (and assuming it would be a long wait for a response), we called house-keeping who promised to contact maintenance for us. Happily, we changed and went off to the pool for a few hours. Back in the room to get ready for dinner, we check the shower--and wouldn't you know it--same as before. So on the way out for dinner we stop at the bell desk (lines for check-in were now longer than ever!) to tell them of our shower problem and were promised that someone would be up to take a look. Arriving back in the room sometime around midnight, we check the shower again--still broken. Now, I was getting upset--actually panicking at the thought of not being able to have a shower the next morning--so I decided to pack up our stuff while my husband went down to the front desk to explain--politely--our situation with the shower. He came back up with a room upgrade. The hotel itself is gorgeous with the giant aquarium behind front desk and the atruim leading to the casino with tropical flowers. The restaurants' food was okay--too pricey in my opinion for what you get....but when is Vegas (or anything within a hotel's property) reasonable anyways? Our upgraded room was clean and stylish--loved the double sinks and separate tub and shower stall in the bathroom. A couple dollars in tip to house-keeping gets you extra bath products! The pool area is beautiful, with a tropical look to it. The pool itself is large, with a waterfall in the middle--a little cold for my liking but my husband didn't complain. Drinks were expensive though :(I can't comment too much on the casino as I am not a serious gambler. I stuck with 3-6 Limit Hold'em and never had to wait more than 5 minutes for a seat at a table. I managed to win some money at the table only to have it all go back to the Vegas economy in the form of Outlet shopping, but I was happy in that I didn't lose any money gambling overall. My husband on the other hand, was up in winnings until he decided to enter the nightly poker tournament one night and placed just one spot out of winning a share of the pot! Ah well, it was all in all a great trip--nice to get away from the kids and be adults again!	
