Jun 7 2009 	I was very happy with our stay at the Mirage	We received an incredible rate of $65 &amp; $84 per night by using the SmarterVegas.com website, and we got the 35Volcano rate. This was by far the cheapest rate I found, and I spoke with some other guests who were pretty floored when they found out what I had paid.We arrived four hours before check-in, and were immediately given a room with a pool view. The rooms were very spacious and updated, and I really liked the bed linens, which I'm picky about. I liked the fact that we didn't have to walk what felt like a half mile to get to the strip from our room, it was a quick walk accross the casino to get to the strip or the pool from the elevator, unlike MGM or Caesar's. The pool was beautiful and uncrowded on Wednesday, but by Friday it was nearly impossible to find a chair after 10:00 AM, much less two together. The pool staff is very good about removing towels from chairs that are clearly unoccupied or &quot;reserved&quot; by others. I simply asked a pool staff member to help me find a chair, and they were very gracious.I checked out the Bare pool because a promoter gave me a free &quot;ladies admission&quot; pass while I was hanging out in the casino. It was a very cool set-up, it was small, crowded with great music and a lot of good looking people enjoying cabanas, dancing and drinking. There were only a couple of people enjoying the European bathing. You could reserve a lounger with a $50 minimum bar tab, which isn't hard to do at $15 a drink (which were very good). The staff at Bare was friendly and fun, and I think it would be a great atmosphere for a bachelorette party.The Mirage location on the Strip was great, as it wasn't a far walk from Fashion Show and lots of inexpensive places to eat. The only thing I would say, is that we had some very rowdy neighbors who had a party IN THE HALLWAY at 2:30 AM, and I called the front desk to have them ask them to move it into their room, and it took about 20 minutes for them to have security respond.Overall, I would definitely stay there again.	
Jun 7 2009 	Fantastic Hotel couldn't have asked for more!	I stayed at the Mirage for 8 nights starting on 5th May 2009, both of us are in our 20's and hadn't stayed at this hotel before. The hotel is absolutely huge and has an amazing swimming pool, which can get a little busy at the weekends, but it didn't bother us at all. It was great seeing everyone in the pool drinking their beers and relaxing. The pool is a huge lagoon style pool and has lots of sun beds, but as usual people start to line up before the pool has opened just to get the best beds, but i suppose this happens in most places. The only thing about the pool that was dissapointing was the fact that the waterfall was broken, apart from that i loved being around the pool. One tip though....take your own drinks as it was very expensive (to us anyway), 7.5 dollars for a bottle of bud.The rooms were amazing, 32 inch TV and very funky decor and the bed was huge!!! we had a pool view which was nice too, but we didn't really spend that much time in there. I had read reviews about the bathrooms being small but we didn't think they were that small!!The staff were very friendly and it was easy to find your way around the hotel, again the only downside to this hotel was the price of the drinks and the food. You can find things alot cheaper but it all depends on your budget, we ate out at other hotels mainly.The cravings buffett was well worth the money, i think it was 18 dollars per head for breakfast and you could eat and drink as much as you like and there was everything you could imagine and more...well worth a visit..or two!!The hotel is probably smack bang in the middle of the strip so getting around was very easy. The duce bus stop is right outside and will take you up and down the strip, including Fremont street for 24 hours for only 7 dollars each....this is a must if your feet get a bit sore...Tip make sure you have the right change for the drivers as they dont carry any!!!Overall i would advise anyone going to Vegas to stay here, i have only stayed in the Excalibur before and although that was a nice hotel this was just soooo much better. We had a fantastic time and loved the hotel.	
Jun 6 2009 	Not for light sleepers but excellent remodel of a great hotel	The Mirage has undergone a modest evolution of late, but the wonderful location, beautiful atrium, and fantastic pool remain the same. The rooms have undergone a terrific remodeling job. Like most hotels that have remodeled, they've ditched the themed rooms in favor of a basic modern motif. However, I actually liked the retro-modern redesign of the rooms, which now boast plush mattresses, a flat screen TV, and dark woods with accents of colors like pink and orange. Now to the bad news. The bathrooms, while remodeled with nice granite counters and tile accents around the mirror, are still tiny. Fine for a solo traveler, but not ideal for a couple or family. And here's the deal breaker for me, as a light sleeper. You can hear EVERYTHING from these rooms. Every door that closes, every word uttered in the hallway, the maids knocking on doors and saying &quot;Room keeping,&quot; the halls being vacuumed. It's a light sleeper's worst nightmare. That said, the Mirage is still a great choice for most, due to its ideal mid-Strip location, excellent pool, and probably the nicest rooms for the money of any four star on the strip.	
Jun 3 2009 	Just Average....	Stayed three nights while my husband attended convention at the hotel. Overall I liked the location – right in the middle of the strip and walking distance to shopping, restaurants, and other casinos. You have to walk from the lobby through the casino to get to the room elevators and it can be a bit of a hike, especially when you are hauling baggage. As a nonsmoker I thought the casino was very smoky and uncomfortable for me to breathe.Room - Our room on the 5th floor was adequate – bed was comfortable, large flat screen TV, good work space. The bathroom was quite small and I noticed rust forming on the tub fixtures. No view really – the rooftop and glass atrium but maybe that’s what you get at the conference rate. As I said, just adequate, not dazzling by any stretch of the imagination.Pool – it is a very nice sprawling pool with a mixture of sun and shade. It is a thousand times better than the TI pool we passed on the tram, but doesn’t hold a candle to the pools at Mandalay Bay. The Mirage pools were FREEZING cold and it was 90 plus degrees outside this week. Hardly anyone goes into the pools because they are so cold so you have lots of room to swim if you want to give it a try. The lounge chairs are not very comfortable and are placed very close together like sardines in a can. We shared a large pina colada at poolside and it was very tasty.Restaurants - We had champagne brunch at the Mirage on Sunday and it was pretty good – wide selection of food and while mostly lukewarm, the entrees had flavor and the service was good. We had the breakfast buffet at the Paris hotel one morning and I was disappointed. I would say the Mirage buffet was just as good as Paris… maybe even a bit better! We had breakfast another morning at the Cravings restaurant and it was very average, but the service was fast.Revolution Lounge – My husband is a big Beatles fan so we stopped by for a drink. Very pricey - $15 for a glass of wine and $8 for a beer. There wasn’t anything in the décor to make you think ‘Beatles,’ except a few video clips on a TV screen and you couldn’t hear what they were saying. The lounge promotes some sort of interactive experience however we didn’t see anything unique at all. The back portion of the lounge was not open every time we checked... still curious about the ‘interactive experience.’Misc – our experience with the Mirage elevators was really good – they were plentiful and quick. Much better than our stay at Mandalay Bay in May. Wireless internet is another story. $15 per day PER COMPUTER meaning my husband and I would have to pay twice for access for each of our laptops. Ridiculous. They don’t charge an extra fee for water usage of a second person in a room so I’m not sure why the hotel feels they can justify extortion for a second laptop connection. And to boot, the connection has been unreliable all three days of our visit. I called the front desk and they told me to use the Ethernet cable which holds me captive to using the laptop in the room. After another call to the front desk I managed to get the wireless charge removed for one day of our stay. Overall this hotel was just average. We booked for the proximity to a conference, however if I were free to choose I would try something else.	
Jun 2 2009 	Definitely we will stay at the Mirage again	Enjoyed our 3 nights. Got a high floor room w/view of volcano as requested. Very nice room, very clean. The pool is wonderful. Wish Starbucks was alot closer to the guest elevators - its location is inconvenient for overnight guests, and there is no inroom coffee. Guest elevators are a wandering trek through the casino after checking in - not fun with luggage and kids. Overall though, we will stay at the Mirage again. All staff that we encountered was freindly and welcoming.	
Jun 2 2009 	Still very nice and they are taking steps to update...	Had a lot of free time on my hands and took the Mirage up on an email Volcano Rate special, and booked a long 10 day trip.- Check in had a few minutes wait (on a Sunday around 5:30pm) not bad at all, but when it was my turn they found my reservation immediately and knew the room type I selected, and the nightly rates I'd booked at.- Room (Deluxe) was great, and clean - bedding had no stray hairs or stains (as some reviews has commented). Bathroom was clean, faucets and drains worked fine (Note that the power vents are not strong enough to remove all the steam from a shower). Hair dryer was very good with multiple settings. - Tipping the housekeeping staff every day (I went $5/day given the recession, and the great deal I got on the room) got me larger size bath soap as well as multiple shaving kits. - Check out went fine, I used the electronic check out. This is a nice feature as it also lets you review your bill during your stay, so you can double-check that you are being charged correctly for the services you've used, etc.Gambling:I typically only play poker. The poker room staff are a great bunch, and I look forward to seeing them 1-2 a year. The waitresses are typically quick, but sometimes you catch a wave where there is a shift change or some other confusion, and you have to wait a bit for service, but they aren't slackers and they aim to please, so be a bit patient if you hit them when they're out of step. Poker room comps: Every other day, or if you get in 8+ hrs in one day, they will give you a $15 food voucher. (The poker room offers a poker room rate that you can book at. You must average 6/hrs night Su-Th, and 8/hrs night Fr-Sa, which is a fair amount of play. These days you can find comparable rates online).I also played the table game Pai Gow a few times. The dealers there were friendly, and rooted for the customers - which is always nice. The waitresses were on it the few times I was there.The buffet (I actually only had breakfast/brunch there. Brunch once, breakfast 5-6 times) is very good. It may not have the extensive variety of some higher priced buffet options, but what's provided is prepared well and tastes great. I found the staff to be pleasant and while it some time took a minute or two for them to get my initial drink order they were on it after that. (This trip I found that the staff responded with &quot;Thanks I appreciate it&quot; when I tipped).Pros: Great location. Refurbished rooms are very nice. Nice pool.Temporary Con: They were working on improvements around the set of elevators which took me to my room. This meant that 3 of the elevators were out of service for a week. This only caused a problem on Saturday and Sunday late afternoon early evening. The hotel took action by routing some people to a service elevator (which was a bit hard to get to, but they led you there). Later in the week they shifted the work area and 4 of the 6 elevators were in service, and there were no longer any backups.Pro/Con: (Didn't affect my trip) Pool's waterfall was shut down. Some other guests were upset about this, and while I do enjoy the waterfall in theory, I must say having it off made the seating area near it a lot quieter.Con: The drink prices at the pool are very expensive. A Bud beer was $8. A bucket of five Buds was $32. I found that the frozen drinks had very little alcohol in them. Some will find the bathrooms a bit small. I know the bathrooms at Mandalay Bay and Bellagio are bigger, as are those in the higher priced rooms at the Mirage.I dinged the service because of the elevator issue - I think it could have been planned better, as the elevators were out of service even when the area was not being worked on.Noteworthy: They've added an indoor/outdoor bar, as well as a Starbucks, where the amenities store (up front) was. (They'd earlier added a BLT burger restaurant where the front tiger cage was). (They already had a nice coffee shop in the rear stores, and it's still open). I didn't stop in to either the bar of Starbucks as I was typically on the go, but the outdoor bar space looks like a nice place to chill and a good use of the space.Tips: I recommend the breakfast buffet if you are staying at the restaurant. Pricewise it makes sense. If you order a coffee/tea, juice, eggs and a side at the cafe (etc), then you're up to $15 anyway (the breakfast buffet is 15.03 w/tax). With the buffet you don't have to overeat, and you can have what you want. Additionally, I personally really like the brunch w/alcohol option (available Sat and Sun). Many of the on property restaurants are offerring happy hour or other dining specials. I didn't get a chance to try them out, but they sounded nice.Local eats: If you want a cheap breakfast you can run across the street to McD. They've added a Chipotle across the street as well, another great lighter (but filling) meal option. My other favorite option is Outback across the street - I like their Margaritas better than Margaritaville.	
Jun 1 2009 	Renovation Rules	Once upon a time the Mirage was the elite hotel on The Strip, setting the standards for customer service and luxury accomodations. Sadly, that is no longer the case. While the Mirage is still a very nice property, it now is a step below hotels like Wynn, Encore, and Venetian.For our weeklong stay, my girlfriend and I booked a room on the &quot;private&quot; access floors. Unfortunately, one of the two elevators servicing those floors was closed for several days for renovations to the elevator lobby. This resulted in occassional long waits for the elevator, and crowded rides when the elevator did show up. The pool area was very crowded. Not helping was the fact a portion of the pool area was closed for renovations. This also meant the waterfall features were not operating, turning the acclaimed Mirage pool into your typical Las Vegas resort hotel pool. I'm curious why the renovations and repairs weren't completed while the pool was closed during the &quot;off season&quot;.On the positive side, the recently renovated rooms were quite sharp and comfortable. Bathrooms were large and clean. The 42 inch flat screen TV was nice. Staff members were courteous and pleasant. The hotel offers a nice mix of shops, restaurants and services.On the downside, although the check-in lines were short, service was slow (about 15 minutes). The concierge staff were indifferent, at one time referring me to the hotel Business Center, when the center was long closed for the day. Room doors slammed rather forcefully upon closing. Food at certain restaurants like the Carnegie Deli was unexpectedly expensive. Looking for cheap drinks? Not at the Mirage, as one waitress confided to us the drink prices are &quot;outrageous&quot;. We still drank...just not as much.Overall, in my opinion the level of service and quality have slipped under MGM/Mirage management. The vibe of the hotel has changed. After witnessing a shirtless 20 something with shorts past his butt and baseball cap cocked sideways strut around the casino floor, I wondered if he would've made it past security 10 years ago. After all, most 7-11's won't even serve you without a shirt.....The Mirage isn't a bad hotel....it's just no longer the great Las Vegas hotel.	
