Jun 1 2009 	Will stay here again	Located right on the strip. We booked 4 nights thru the internet months in advance and got a rate of $90/night. Then we booked a 2- nignt extension a few days before arrival and got a rate of $135/night. Lesson learned: book months in advance if possible.Room is spacious and very clean. Bathroom is also spacious and very clean. There is a good size safe in the room, large enough to hold a laptop and cameras. There is a fridge stocked with snacks and drinks. Don't touch anything in fridge unless you are willing to pay the outrageous prices. If you pick up an item and put it back, you are charged for it. Internet access is available for a fee of $15.00/day.Bed is very comfortable.  The buffet is excellent, but expensive. We went to the Harrah's buffet across the street which is just as good or better.. Overall, very nice hotel and will definitely stay here again when visiting Las Vegas.	
May 31 2009 	Last time there	I've been a big fan of the Mirage for years, the last 10 years in fact.The location is central. The pool has always been better than most.The rooms were larger and more comfortable than others on the strip.I guess Memorial Day weekend is a bad time to visit if you want any sort of calm. Beyond the chaos at the pool, the hotel is beginning to look run down. This despite the rooms being remodeled over the last couple years.The dresser drawer handle was broken in my room and the scratch patterns across the drawer fronts indicated that this had been a problem for some time. Every other day, the maid would stick the handle back on the screw but either the screw or handle had been stripped and it just came off again. Other low-lights were the electricity going out in the bathroom one day, only part of the bathroom so it wasn't the ground fault switch. Also there was no hot water in the hotel one evening, I have not seen that in a large hotel in North America before. The elevators have a mind of their own and will change direction partway up to your floor.These things by themselves are hardly vacation breakers but think about why you are booking this hotel, are you booking to get a cheap bed or are you looking for the Vegas experience they promise. The reality is that the owners of the hotel are heavily invested in a large complex being built and there is no money being spent here. Discount rates are great but they are attracting a different crowd than the hotel used to service. Theres just so much staggering and vomit that you can put up with. Anyone over 35 pretty much echoed this sentiment while we were there.If its your first time to Vegas the glitz will most likely distract you from much of the problems. If you're a reasonably frequent visitor, the warts will show. Despite the cut backs in staffing, the remaining employees were quite nice and were trying hard, its just too bad the expansion greed has crippled the owners.	
May 30 2009 	Convenient And Semi-Luxurious	Stayed at the Mirage from February 19-23 for my wedding. The review is a little late, because I have been extremely busy, but better late than never. Check in was quick because we arrived around 10:30 pm, and upon inquiring we were given an upgrade in our room. Them room was spacious, nicely decorated, and the bed was extremely comfortable. The hotel is situated on the strip in between Caesar's and Treasure Island, a block away from the Fashion Show mall, and across the strip from Harrah's. The hotel is nice with a rain forest in the atrium and a large aquarium in the lobby. We ate at the buffet for breakfast and brunch and they were both excellent. The deli and burger place inside are both good, but extremely expensive. You'll end up paying over $45 on a meal for two at either place. Mcdonalds and Chipotle are across the street. The pool was open but it was chilly out so there weren't to many people using the pool. The hotel is large, but not so extremely big that you would get lost. There is a tram that connects the Mirage to Treasure Island. Nothing bad to say about this hotel aside from the price. The hotel can be over priced if you are unable to find a deal.	
