May 23 2009 	Oasis in a Sea of Machines	During the last leisurely visit to Las Vegas, the Bellagio was the &quot;in&quot; resort and Ceasars was run down. Things have changed, including the Mirage. The walk from the entrance and lobby was fairly short and effortless while passing some slot machines. Since the casino floor is not that large at the Mirage, you are not walking for a long period of time amongst folks sitting at machines gambling.The room on the 24th floor was recently remodeled, fairly clean and spacious. The layout was practical. Closets on both sides of the bed helpful in sorting out clothes. Like one previous reviewer noted, the carpet is dark, so every piece of lint is visible. The flat screen TV also a nice feature. Plenty of lamps and lighting in the room. We also liked that the windows could be opened out slightly, especially during the volcano show.The bathroom was plenty spacious for two people to get ready for the day or evening. The light around the mirror is a nice decor feature. The shower head would not move, thus you had to accept whatever way the spray came out. Toilet flush did it's job nicely and quickly.The pool was fun and clean. Unlike a previous reviewer, the pool smelled of chlorine, not sour. Every pool patron behaved and kept to themselves. Many times large pools invite rowdiness, however this was not the case. While the pool water fall was not working, it was hardly missed. Plenty of trees, vegetation, piped-in music and birds around to create a calm environment. Pool staff attentive as needed.As with most other visitors, we did wander through other casino resorts. Surprisingly, the Bellagio is really run-down and the color scheme odd. Ceasars completely remodeled-gone are the smoky-colored mirrored glass and gaudy gold accents amongst thousands of lightbulbs flashing. The Wynn and Encore decor is very pleasing to the eyes, plenty of wonderful places to relax, play or just watch the world. The Palazzo had this very open and large feel, somewhat boxy feeling in the casino. The Venetian was just ok.The visit also included seeing legandary Tom Jones at MGM. The show and performance was great. Not a bad seat in the house, although we were right up front. The MGM itself is tired and seems to have lost it's theme. We did eat at Craftsteak. Excellent.Bottom line, if you come to Las Vegas and the Mirage to gamble, you'll get just that. If you want a rest from gambling, Mirage has that also. Las Vegas is not known for culture or history, so don't expect that.	
May 22 2009 	First time at The Mirage...won't be the last!	After my first trip to Vegas I had always wanted to stay at The Mirage. The grounds looked so beautiful and the place had this ambiance to it. After contemplating summer vacation for a while, I came across some great deals through the Mirage website and also noticed they had recently renovated the standard rooms....I was sold. We stayed 5/10-5/13 and got an amazing deal (~$70/night I believe). We arrived at 9am and were told that earliest we could check-in would be 11am if rooms were available. No problem at all as we left our bags with the bellmen who were friendly and extremely helpful. After a quick bite to eat we were able to check-in at 11am and were given an upgraded room on the 23rd floor with a strip/volcano view upon request. It's amazing what a smile and a little kindness can get you. I find myself incredibly annoyed by a lot of the reviews on this website. First and foremost...you're in Las Vegas. The hotels are huge, sorry that you might have to walk a little ways to get somewhere. GET OVER IT...most people who complain about this probably NEED the exercise anyway! The hotel is large, but in my opinion, very cozy and welcoming. The atrium is absolutely beautiful and we found the casino to be very clean...somewhat smokey but what casino in Vegas isn't? Slots seemed tight compared to other casinos. Didn't play table games as limits are too high at night when we prefer to gamble. Did have a slight problem with elevators the first day (Sunday) we were there due to repairs. Other guests seems to be really annoyed but we never waited for more than a minute or two to catch one - no problem Mon/Tues as they had opened an additional one. Our room was absolutely beautiful (pictures included) and housekeeping does an amazing job keeping things neat. Probably the most comfortable bed I have ever slept on in my entire life. The walls do seem a little thin, especially in the morning as people are coming and going, but again...it's a large hotel so this is to be somewhat expected. The bathroom is a bit small but how much time do you really spend in a bathroom anyway? Clean towels were always replenished and we never had to ask for anything. Our housekeeper even took time to layout our toiletries and other items we brought on top of a washcloth on the sink...above and beyond service if you ask me. The pool is absolutely beautiful...very tropical and relaxing and we really enjoyed the hot tubs. They aren't extremely hot, just a little warmer than the pools so don't be afraid to use them....you won't get too hot. It was difficult finding lounge chairs on Sunday but we were able to find some after a couple minutes of walking around. Didn't have any problems finding some on Mon/Tues...I'm sure the pool is much busier on the weekends. The waterfall was not working as I believe they are doing repairs. We were a little disappointed, but the section of the pool that was closed off was rather small, so again...no big deal and not worth getting upset over. The pool isn't open as late as most people would expect, but it is Las Vegas and times are pretty standard across the board at all casinos. I think the hours are posted on the website...with a little research you can be self-informed PRIOR to your trip. We had meals at California Pizza Kitchen and BLT Burger...good food/service and great options for something more middle-ground in pricing. We also ate at Mesa Grill (Bobby Flay's restaurant) in Caesar's Palace...outstanding service, and perfectly prepared/seasoned/balanced flavors. It's easy to understand his celebrated &quot;celebrity-chef&quot; status after enjoying a meal there. We had an amazing time at Mirage and will certainly stay again next time we're in Vegas. The service, amenities, and location are outstanding. In addition, I highly recommend checking out the following places while in Vegas:- Bellagio Fountains/Mirage Volcano/MGM Grand Lion Habitat- Forum Shops at Caesar's Palace for shopping- Fremont Street Downtown (original Vegas charm,; $20 cab including tip; cheap drinks; LOW minimums; LCD show is pretty cool)- O'Sheas (small casino next to Flamingo and across from Caesar's; low minimums; steady drink service; younger (21-35yo) crowd; laid-back/fun atmosphere)- Ballys (low minimums, friendly/helpful dealers, live music)- If you're on a low budget for food, there is a McDonald's/Chipotle/Panda Express right across the street from The Mirage, and a Burger King inside O'Sheas...easy places to hit up for a quick/cheap breakfast or lunch	
