May 18 2009 	Not as good as our last stay	My husband and I stayed at the Mirage Hotel May 11-17, 2009. We've stayed at this hotel two times before. The hotel has since had some renovations, including a redo of the rooms. I have to say, I'm not impressed. This hotel, even with renovations, is showing its age of 20 years....especially compared to other hotels on the strip. Three times I needed to ask for something in our bathroom to be fixed and we could never get our room cool enough. Also, the huge water fall at the pool, which is a main attraction, was not working. Two huge hunks of the &quot;rock&quot; had fallen off and were very slowly being repaired. I should say that it wasn't horrible, in fact it was nice; however, next year we will be staying at the Palazzo where we stayed last year.	
May 17 2009 	Good hotel great location.	Someone else in my group picked this hotel, but I was pleased with the Mirage. My room was clean and comfortable and good value. I could hear people talking in the hallways and in the room next door, so light sleepers might want to stay somewhere else. There are several restaurants and a coffee shop in the hotel. The casino is nice, with a good poker room, but they need more blackjack tables; I found myself waiting for a spot to open up more than once. The pool was nice, but they push all the beach chairs together in long rows so you'll be sharing your afternoon with strangers. The Mirage is in a great location, right in the middle of the Strip and in walking distance to most of the other casinos. The Forum shops at Caesar's are right next door, giving you many other options for shopping and dining. I would stay here again.	
May 17 2009 	Great trip - good hotel	I have just returned from a great trip to Las Vegas as part of a group of 4 fairly low-maintainence guys 30yrs old or under. It was my 3rd trip to Vegas, and 3rd time at the Mirage.ROOM:+Beds were very comfortable+Room was cleaned regularly+Nice tv and interactive services+Was given a room with fantastic volcano view and view of the strip-Bathroom was quite small and shower lacked power-Door slamming/corridor noise sometimes disturbed restRESORT:+Well kept grounds and casino cleanliness was pleasing to the eye+Pool scene was great - played good music, was busy without being overcrowded+Popular and stylish nightclub+Popular Cirque du Soleil show+Perfect location on the strip, can walk to many popular hotels and shopping facilities-Slots/machines notoriously tight-Some of the floors are having renovation work on the elevators and had huge queues when it was busy on the weekend (fortunately I was not on those floors)FOOD/DRINK:+Good selection of bars +Good range of casual dining, pizza, deli (24 hour), American, international, buffet, coffee shop+Portions were of a generous size-Poolside service drinks very expensive - $9 for a botle of water! We ended up buying a $3 bottle from the shop and taking it in-Poolside snacks were expensive and of a poor standard-Not enough healthy options in most restaurants other than a Caesar salad (with the exception of the pizza place)STAFF/SERVICE:+Check in staff were very polite and was delighted with the room I was given+Poolside staff were attentive and friendly+Maids cleaned the room regularlyOVERALL:I had a great stay at the Mirage and being my 3rd visit I knew what to expect. My primary reasons for coming back are the comfort of the rooms and the location of the hotel in relation to the other major hotels. It is expensive for what it is, and having spoken to some Vegas regulars while I was out there I may try somewhere else next time to see if I can get more 'bang for my buck'. I would certainly recommend this hotel to any newish visitors to Vegas as it's a great base to explore the strip from.	
May 15 2009 	Mirage never dissapoints!	I have visited Vegas five times, 4 of which I have stayed at The Mirage. For my wife &amp; me this is the perfect hotel, with the perfect location. We stayed 5 nights, for which I paid $70 each of four nights and one night at $160. I think it was a great deal (I used codes from fatwallet.com). We had a rental car. From the moment we arrived at the north valet of The Mirage we were greeted by a really nice valet guy who welcomed us and asked us if we needed any information. He quickly sent somebody to take our luggage. Lines at check-in were a little long but nothing to complain about. We arrived at 1 pm. Again a very nice lady at the front desk greeted us and welcomed us. She gave us our requested room. I asked her if I could get a line pass for the buffet and she gave us a line pass for all our stay for the buffet, California PIzza Kitchen and Carnegie. Our room was great, it was the standard no strip view but it was fine. I called the belldesk and in 5 min our bags came in. A very nice guy asked us if we found everything ok in the room and if we needed anything. One little downside of the standard room is that the bathroom which is a little small but we didn't care. The hotel ambiance was elegant and fun, as always. Vegas vibe at its best. Wife couldn't wait to get to the Fashion Show Mall so we went using the tram to TI and then the bridge. One thing I like the most from The Mirage is the fantastic pool. Get as early as you can because thre is a line to get in!! Our entire stay was perfect, thanks to all the nice staff at this hotel.	
May 15 2009 	Mirage was just OK - read on for the good and the not so good	We just returned from the Mirage. We booked through our travel agent - I don't know if we had any substantial savings going that route, but it was nice to be dealing with an indivdual rather than just the web - I'll explain some of the pros and cons of that later.About the Mirage:Pros: We ended up with a nice room overlooking the volcano and some of the strip. The pool was not as crowded as I had heard, but you did need to get there early to get a good chair (8:00 am open) The buffet (cravings) is one of the best in town. The location is great - right in the middle of the strip. Walking distance from many of the other resorts (Ceasars Palace, Ballagio, Harrahs, Flamingo, Ballys, Paris, Venetian, Pallazzo, Wynn, etc...). Our room (26024) was comfortable although not very plush. The walk from the room elevators to the pool was not as bad as some of the other resorts (i.e. Bally;s) but not as good as Venetian or Pallazzo. For the most part I found the staff to be friendly and helpful. Check in did not take that long (15-20 minutes).The Cons: Room - The first two rooms we had - were not great. The first room was on the 14th floor and overlooked the pool. The bathroom was very small with no shower (except in the tub). Think motel 6 bathroom and then divide by two and you kind of get the idea. The bathroom did have a nice makeup mirror that unfortunatly would not turn on. Maintenance did respond promptly to attempt a repair on the wallhung mirror but then explained that those type of makeup mirrors had proved to be defective and they had been removing them from the rooms - he did not know why this room still had one. Another unfortunate problem with this room was the bird do-do smeared on the window. When I called to request a different room the gal at the from desk was very accomodating and transfered us to a room on the 21st floor (I think). This room had been recently remodeled and had a much better bathroom (although still on the small side) with a seperate shower and tub. This room had no view at all and also had no makeup mirror - which as you can probably tell by now was a big deal to my wife. One more call to the front desk and again the girl was very helpfull. I explained that I would be willing to pay for an upgraded room - to which she said that was not neccesary and arranged for us to relocate to a room with a view. This room was much better but it had not been remodeled so it did not have the larger flat screen TV or the ports for us to plug out Ipods into - which turned out to be sad because my wife had loaded a couple of movies onto her ipod that we had planned to watch - oh well. You could hear noises from the hall when other guests were going by talking but it did not seem to be that bad. We also could hear some elevator noise - but we had requested to be close to the elevators so I guess thats to be expected. They were still doing some major remodeling - which meant that the elevator areas on the ground floor had some jackhammering going on behind plastic sheets and sometimes you had no light in the hallway were the elevators were.  Pool - As I mentioned earlier you need to arrive early to get a good chair - but even when we arrived later in the day - we were able to find some chairs. The water was cold! I know that this is typical for many Vegas pools - but you need to be aware of this. Later in the summer it probably feels better. The hot tubs were warm. The pool waterfalls were not working while we were there which was disappointing. Gambling - The machines at the Mirage seemed very tight to me and we gambled enough there to know. The nice part was that our meals which we charged to our room all ended up being comped. Restaurants - Loved the &quot;Cravings&quot; buffet. Prime Rib, Shrimp, and desserts, and overall selection were all great. BLT was just OK with lack luster service and overpriced hamburgers - which did come out the way I ordered it. Carnegie Deli was OK if you like that kind of food. They bring you a plate of pickels right off the bat. Paradise Cafe was a bit of a disappointment. In planning our trip, I had envisioned eating breakfast poolside - this proved to be not so great. This first morning we went to the pool we were told the restaurant did not open until 10:00 - so we grabbed our chairs and waited till 11:00 to go into the restaurant at which time we were told they had stopped serving breakfast. The next day we went into the restaurant at 9:00 (when they opened) and found the breakfasts to be nothing great. The servers were good. My recommendation for a quick continental style breakfast that you can take poolside is to stop at the Roasted Bean just outside the pool area which was great for coffee rolls, and muffins.Comments on Vegas in general: Gambling - Don't gamble more than what you brought to lose - my wife and I decide before we go how much we are willing to lose and that is what we gamble. NO MORE THAN THAT! Getting around - Be prepared to walk a lot. Even if you decide to stay in one resort - you will find yourself doing a lot of walking. If you are going to properly see the strip, downtown or some of the many shopping venues than you will be doing a lot of walking. We use taxi's, buses, trams etc... all of which are great ways to get around - but they do cost. Money - Vegas is tourist central. Be prepared for everything to cost more than at home. A bottle of pop at the resort is typically $3.00 or more. A dinner buffet can be $30 per person. A good trick is to show up for dinner at the end of the lunch cycle (around 3:00 - 4:00pm) pay lunch price and have an early dinner for about $19 per person. There are also tons of &quot;free&quot; things to do in Vegas - don't overlook how fantastic some of those are.  Getting there - We have driven from Denver 15 hours and we have flown 1 1/2 hours. It is really nice to have a vehicle while there but not entirely necessary. When we have a vehicle we go to Walmart and stock up on snacks and pops rather than pay the hotel prices and its easy to visit many locations. We booked through a travel agent and we decided to fly this time. We flew on Southwest and as you may know they do not assign seats but rather they let you &quot;check - in&quot; for your flight 24 hours before it leaves. When you check in they give you a boarding pass which basically gives you your place in line to enter the plane. Then you can pick from whichever seats are left. We had paper tickets which meant that we could not use the electronic kiosks at the luggage check in counter. I don't know which way is better but it felt like we were being overlooked while they were calling the names of people that had used the kiosks to check their bags while we waited in another line. We decided to arrive early and leave late to keep it to only three nights but gain the benefit of four full days. The problem with that way of thinking is that the hotel won't check you into your room until approx. 3:00 - not a problem if your prepared. We checked our bags with the bell staff, kept our carry ons with us which had a swimsuit each and headed to the pool. Would have been a great plan if we also had our sunscreen with us - but did not want to put sunscreen in our carryon's with the current liquid restrictions on the airlines. Leaving late was not a great idea. The hotel will require you to check out at noon (we were able to get them to extend it to 1:00) which meant that the bell staff had to hold our luggage until it was time for us to head to the airport. This also meant that we needed to stay somewhat nearby to get our luggage. Add on top of this that we had both had our fill of gambling by this time and did not want to do anymore walking it made for a long, long day. In retrospect I should have had an earlier flight home. Final comments - Vegas is a great place for a short visit and you will see amazing things and amazing people.	
May 15 2009 	Good overall experience...	We checked in on a Saturday night, around 9pm, and we did not have to wait. Our room, which was just an average king sized bed room, looked just like the pictures do. The room was decorated nicely. The bathroom was definitely small and the A.C. wasn't the greatest. The room stayed comfortable, but we had to turn the temperature down into the 60s. When you walked out into the hallway, it was freezing...the hallways must have been 55F, seriously. The refrigerator does operate on a weighted system, so if you pick anything up, you will be charged. Room service did ok the first day, and much better the next day with a tip.The pool was nice. All the rumors are true about being there early. We went down right at 8am and there was a line all the way back into the hotel from the pool area with people trying to get in. Drinks are sooo expensive! There really wasn't very much alcohol in them either. We went into the 'Secret Garden.' It was nice and would be a good attraction for kids. The volcano is a fun attraction as well...of course it is only 5 minutes long and people line up for that early too.We ate at the buffet for breakfast and enjoyed the omelet bar. We ate at Carib Cafe...I would not recommend that place. You can probably make better food at home. BLT burger was a great place. We ate at Japanois on the last night we were there. The setting is great and the service is very helpful and friendly. You do not get a lot of food for the money...if you are on a budget or like to eat...you will be unhappy with Japanois. Rhumbar has a relaxing atmosphere with the outside lounge.All employees we interacted with were nice. Drink service was just 'ok' in my opinion. Slot machines are in fact tight, but I did have luck with the &quot;Deal or No Deal&quot; slots. They are fun to play and you get to pick briefcases...try it!I would stay at The Mirage again.	
